independent_work.et:
Students are required to read one article (from the selection provided by the instructor) before the lecture and write a reaction paper to the article three times throughout the course. One time during the course the students are asked to write a reaction paper based on their own experience. All in all, students are expected to write 3 reaction papers to articles, and one personal reaction paper (4 papers in total).
Each reaction paper to an article is 1 page in length with no title page, and it should include four components:
- An idea/conclusion/implication of the article that you agree with;
- An idea/conclusion/implication of the article you do not (fully) agree with;
- Questions that arise for the reader, but remain unanswered by the article (could include more general questions, discussion questions, e.g., about the applicability in other contexts, or questions arising from personal experience);
- Thougths on the usefulness of the knowledge that the article presents.
Each component should refer back to a particular section in the article and explain *why* the reader is of a particular opinion or position.
The reaction paper based on personal experience is also 1 page in length with no title page and should relate the personal experience about visiting an informal context (museum, zoo, etc.) to the ideas presented during the course. The reaction paper should cover an explanation of and evaluation of (1) the learning opportunities present in the context, (2) their personal learning experience, and (3) factors that affected their learning experience.
Extra credit can be earned by students by writing a follow-up to their own reaction paper answering the questions they raised after the lecture, but before the final exam.
In additions, each prerecorded lecture is followed by a small engagement/comprehension task in the moodle the student has to finish. These tasks combined provide 8 points in total towards the final grade.
